The error you're encountering is because the `clearData()` function is called within the `cleardata.js` file, and it's trying to access the checkbox elements that are in the `cleardata.html` file. To resolve this, you can use the `window.postMessage()` method to communicate between the iframe containing `cleardata.html` and the `cleardata.js` script.

First, modify the `cleardata.html` file, adding an `id` attribute to the SVG element and moving the `cleardata.js` script reference back to `popup.html`:

```html
<!doctype html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Cache Cleaner Button</title>
    <style>
        body { font-family: Arial, sans-serif; }
        .svg-container {
          width: 50%;
          max-width: 200px;
        }
        svg {
          display: inline-block;
          width: 100%;
          height: auto;
          cursor: pointer;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="svg-container">
        <!-- Your SVG code goes here -->
        <svg id="clear-data-button" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" id="Capa_1" viewBox="0 0 512 512" preserveAspectRatio="xMidYMid meet">
            <!-- SVG content -->
        </svg>
    </div>
</body>
</html>
```

Next, update the `popup.html` file with the following changes:

```html
<!doctype html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Cache Cleaner Popup</title>
    <script src="cleardata.js"></script>
</head>
<body>
    <iframe id="cleardata-frame" src="cleardata.html" frameborder="0" width="100%" height="100%"></iframe>
    <script>
        // Listen for a message from cleardata.html
        window.addEventListener("message", function(event) {
            // Check if the message is coming from the same extension
            if (event.origin !== window.location.origin) return;
            // Call the clearData function when the SVG is clicked
            if (event.data === "clearData") {
                clearData();
            }
        });

        // Add a click event listener to the SVG in cleardata.html
        document.getElementById("cleardata-frame").addEventListener("load", function() {
            const svgElement = this.contentWindow.document.getElementById("clear-data-button");
            svgElement.addEventListener("click", function() {
                window.postMessage("clearData", window.location.origin);
            });
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

In `popup.html`, the click event listener added to the SVG in `cleardata.html` triggers `window.postMessage()`. The message is then listened for by the parent window, and the `clearData()` function is called upon receiving this message.

With these changes, your addon should function correctly without encountering the null element error.
